Params

Setting output, environments, libraries and temporary directories.

First the directories for workflow output, conda and conda environments used by Herper, R libaries from Renv and for temporary files must be created.

dir.create(output_dir, showWarnings = FALSE, recursive = TRUE)

Build Herper conda and conda environments.

In this section Conda and Conda environments required for processing and analysis are installed. The conda environment is described within a Conda yml lock file and the R/Bioconductor Herper package is used the required environment and conda to install to the listed local directory.

general_conda <- file.path(output_dir, "libraries_and_environments", "brc_conda")
general_env <- {
  Herper::import_CondaEnv(yml_import = "general_env2.yml", name = "general_rnaseq", pathToMiniConda = general_conda)

  "general_rnaseq"
}

Create whitelisted fasta file

This section descibes how we create our reference fasta file

DR11_whitelist <- {
  options(timeout = 600 * 60)
  download.file("https://rubioinformatics.s3.amazonaws.com/Reference/DR11_whiteListChr.txt", file.path(output_dir, "DR11_whiteListChr.txt"))
  DR11_whitelist_MD5 <- tools::md5sum(file.path(output_dir, "DR11_whiteListChr.txt"))
  if (DR11_whitelist_MD5 == "39bbe0c833299011b6c5e436b15b2e16") {
    write.table(DR11_whitelist_MD5, file.path(output_dir, "DR11_whitelist_MD5.txt"))
  } else {
    unlink(file.path(output_dir, "DR11_whiteListChr.txt"))
    stop("Calculated MD5 didn't match expected")
  }
  file.path(output_dir, "DR11_whiteListChr.txt")
}
DR11_fasta <- {
  options(timeout = 600 * 60)
  download.file("https://rubioinformatics.s3.amazonaws.com/Reference/Danio_rerio.GRCz11.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz", file.path(output_dir, "Danio_rerio.GRCz11.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz"))
  DR11_fasta_MD5 <- tools::md5sum(file.path(output_dir, "Danio_rerio.GRCz11.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz"))
  if (DR11_fasta_MD5 == "846df3c5c2e025766574b92cc6cdd07a") {
    write.table(DR11_fasta_MD5, file.path(output_dir, "DR11_fasta_MD5.txt"))
  } else {
    unlink(file.path(output_dir, "Danio_rerio.GRCz11.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz"))
    stop("Calculated MD5 didn't match expected")
  }
  file.path(output_dir, "Danio_rerio.GRCz11.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz")
}
dr11_Bzipped <- {
  unzipped <- gunzip(DR11_fasta, destname = tempfile(), remove = FALSE)
  bgzip(unzipped, dest = file.path(output_dir, "dr11_Bzipped.fa.bgz"), overwrite = TRUE)
  file.path(output_dir, "dr11_Bzipped.fa.bgz")
}
dr11_BzippedIndex <- {
  indexFa(dr11_Bzipped)
  "dr11_Bzipped.fa.bgz.fai"
}
dr11_BzippedWhite <- {
  FaFile <- FaFile(file = dr11_Bzipped, index = dr11_BzippedIndex)
  WhiteListChrs <- read.table(DR11_whitelist, header = TRUE, row.names = 1) %>% rownames()
  dnastringset <- scanFa(FaFile, as = c("DNAStringSet"))
  fastawhite_File <- tempfile()
  writeXStringSet(dnastringset[WhiteListChrs], file = fastawhite_File)
  bgzip(fastawhite_File, dest = file.path(output_dir, "dr11_BzippedWhite.fa.bgz"))
  file.path(output_dir, "dr11_BzippedWhite.fa.bgz")
}
dr11_BzippedWhiteIndex <- {
  indexFa(dr11_BzippedWhite)
  file.path(output_dir, "dr11_BzippedWhite.fa.bgz.fai")
}

Create whitelisted gene models as GTF

This section descibes how we create the GTF files containing gene models to count over.

DR11_gtf <- {
  options(timeout = 600 * 60)
  download.file("https://rubioinformatics.s3.amazonaws.com/Reference/Danio_rerio.GRCz11.110.chr.gtf.gz", file.path(output_dir, "Danio_rerio.GRCz11.110.chr.gtf.gz"))
  DR11_gtf_MD5 <- tools::md5sum(file.path(output_dir, "Danio_rerio.GRCz11.110.chr.gtf.gz"))
  if (DR11_gtf_MD5 == "d963508c829b7afd905ea9b41b154964") {
    write.table(DR11_gtf_MD5, file.path(output_dir, "DR11_gtf_MD5.txt"))
  } else {
    unlink(file.path(output_dir, "Danio_rerio.GRCz11.110.chr.gtf.gz"))
    stop("Calculated MD5 didn't match expected")
  }
  file.path(output_dir, "Danio_rerio.GRCz11.110.chr.gtf.gz")
}
dr11_BzippedGTF <- {
  WhiteListChrs <- read.table(DR11_whitelist, header = TRUE, row.names = 1) %>% rownames()
  gtfGR <- rtracklayer::import.gff(DR11_gtf)
  gtfGR <- gtfGR[seqnames(gtfGR) %in% WhiteListChrs]
  tempgtf <- paste0(tempfile(), ".gtf")
  rtracklayer::export.gff(gtfGR, con = tempgtf)
  bgzip(tempgtf, dest = file.path(output_dir, "dr11_gBzipped.gtf.bgz"), overwrite = TRUE)
}

Build transcript fasta

This section descibes how we build the fasta file of transcript sequences.

dr11_WhiteTransFastaBzipped <- {
  WhiteListChrs <- read.table(DR11_whitelist, header = TRUE, row.names = 1) %>% rownames()
  outFile <- paste0(tempfile(), ".fa")
  txdb <- makeTxDbFromGFF(dr11_BzippedGTF)
  allTranscripts <- exonsBy(txdb, use.names = T, by = "tx")
  fasta_file <- FaFile(dr11_BzippedWhite, index = dr11_BzippedWhiteIndex)
  transSeqs <- extractTranscriptSeqs(fasta_file, allTranscripts[seqnames(allTranscripts) %in%
    WhiteListChrs])
  writeXStringSet(transSeqs, file = outFile)
  bgzip(outFile, dest = file.path(output_dir, "dr11_WhiteTransFasta.fa.bgz"))
  file.path(output_dir, "dr11_WhiteTransFasta.fa.bgz")
}
Import genomic features from the file as a GRanges object ... OK
Prepare the 'metadata' data frame ... OK
Make the TxDb object ... Warning: The "phase" metadata column contains non-NA values for features of type
  stop_codon. This information was ignored.
OK

dr11_gentrome <- {
  transscriptStringset <- readDNAStringSet(dr11_WhiteTransFastaBzipped)
  genomeStringset <- readDNAStringSet(dr11_BzippedWhite)
  gentromeStringset <- c(transscriptStringset, genomeStringset)
  outFile <- paste0(tempfile(), ".fa")
  writeXStringSet(gentromeStringset, file = outFile)
  bgzip(outFile, file.path(output_dir, "dr11_gentrome.fa.bgz"))
  file.path(output_dir, "dr11_gentrome.fa.bgz")
}

Build Salmon index

This section descibes how we create the salmon index files.

dr11_decoy4salmon <- {
  FastaFile <- FaFile(file = dr11_BzippedWhite, index = dr11_BzippedWhiteIndex)
  chroms <- seqinfo(FastaFile)
  write.table(as.data.frame(chroms) %>% rownames(), file = file.path(output_dir, "dr11_decoy4salmon.txt"), sep = "\t", row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE)
  file.path(output_dir, "dr11_decoy4salmon.txt")
}
dr11_salmonIndex <- {
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      command <- "salmon"
      args <- c("index", "-t", dr11_gentrome, "-d", dr11_decoy4salmon, "-p", 4, "-i", file.path(output_dir, "dr11_salmonIndex"))
      processx::run(command, args = args, echo = TRUE)
      file.path(output_dir, "dr11_salmonIndex")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}

Create Hisat2 index for reference genome (Rhisat2)

This section descibes how we build the the index files for Rhisat2 alignment.

dr11_splicesites <- {
  temp <- paste0(tempfile(), ".gtf")
  outfile <- gsub("\\.bgz", ".splicesites", dr11_BzippedGTF)
  gunzip(dr11_BzippedGTF, destname = temp, ext = "bgz", FUN = gzfile, remove = FALSE)
  Rhisat2::extract_splice_sites(temp, outfile)
  return(outfile)
}
dr11_hisat2index <- {
  unzipped_fasta <- paste0(tempfile(), ".fa")
  gunzip(dr11_BzippedWhite, destname = unzipped_fasta, ext = "bgz", FUN = gzfile, remove = FALSE)
  hisat2_build(references = unzipped_fasta, outdir = file.path(output_dir, "dr11_hisat2index"), force = TRUE, prefix = "index")
  file.path(output_dir, "dr11_hisat2index", "index.1.ht2")
}

Build sequence dictionary files for Picard

Here we create sequence dictionary files required for Picard.

dr11_dictionary <- {
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      tempFasta <- paste0(tempfile(), ".fa")
      gunzip(dr11_BzippedWhite, destname = tempFasta, ext = "bgz", FUN = gzfile, remove = FALSE)
      command <- paste0("picard", " ", "CreateSequenceDictionary", " ", "R=", tempFasta, " ", "O=", file.path(output_dir, "dr11_dictionary.dict"))
      ruTargets::system(command)
      file.path(output_dir, "dr11_dictionary.dict")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}

Create whitelisted genepred

This section descibes how we create the genepred files containing gene models.

dr11_genepred <- {
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      gtftogenepred <- "gtfToGenePred"
      tempGTF <- paste0(tempfile(), ".gtf")
      tempPred <- paste0(tempfile(), ".pred")
      gunzip(dr11_BzippedGTF, destname = tempGTF, ext = "bgz", FUN = gzfile, remove = FALSE)
      args <- c("-ignoreGroupsWithoutExons", paste0(tempGTF), paste0(tempPred))
      ruTargets::system2(gtftogenepred, args)
      tempPred %>%
        read.delim(header = FALSE) %>%
        mutate(newname = paste0(V1, "_name")) %>%
        dplyr::select(V1, newname, everything()) %>%
        write.table(file = file.path(output_dir, "dr11_Genes.genepred"), quote = FALSE, row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, sep = "\t")
      file.path(output_dir, "dr11_Genes.genepred")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}

Build Ribosome interval files for Picard

Here we create ribosome interval files required for Picard.

DR11_ribobed <- {
  options(timeout = 600 * 60)
  download.file("https://rubioinformatics.s3.amazonaws.com/Reference/DR11_rRNA.bed", file.path(output_dir, "DR11_rRNA.bed"))
  DR11_ribobed_MD5 <- tools::md5sum(file.path(output_dir, "DR11_rRNA.bed"))
  if (DR11_ribobed_MD5 == "fc50f45f55ee1c9ad7261c26341552f6") {
    write.table(DR11_ribobed_MD5, file.path(output_dir, "DR11_ribobed_MD5.txt"))
  } else {
    unlink(file.path(output_dir, "DR11_rRNA.bed"))
    stop("Calculated MD5 didn't match expected")
  }
  file.path(output_dir, "DR11_rRNA.bed")
}
dr11_ribowhite <- {
  GR <- import.bed(DR11_ribobed)
  WhiteListChrs <- read.table(DR11_whitelist, header = TRUE, row.names = 1) %>% rownames()
  export.bed(GR[seqnames(GR) %in% WhiteListChrs, ], con = file.path(output_dir, "dr11_ribowhite.bed"))
  file.path(output_dir, "dr11_ribowhite.bed")
}
dr11_ribowhiteinterval <- {
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      command <- paste0("picard", " ", "BedToIntervalList", " ", "I=", dr11_ribowhite, " ", "O=", file.path(output_dir, "dr11_ribowhite.interval"), " ", "SD=", dr11_dictionary)
      ruTargets::system(command)
      file.path(output_dir, "dr11_ribowhite.interval")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}

Build events files for Suppa

Here we create sequence dictionary files required for Picard.

dr11_suppa_events <- {
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      tmpdir <- tempdir()
      temp_gtf <- paste0(tempfile(), ".gtf")
      R.utils::gunzip(filename = dr11_BzippedGTF, destname = temp_gtf, remove = FALSE)
      suppa_output <- file.path(output_dir, "dr11_suppa_events", "dr11_suppa_events")
      dir.create(file.path(output_dir, "dr11_suppa_events"))
      args <- c("generateEvents", "-i", temp_gtf, "-e", "SE", "RI", "MX", "FL", "SS", "-f", "ioe", "-o", suppa_output)
      command <- "suppa.py"
      processx::run(command, args = args, echo = TRUE)
      unlink(temp_gtf)
      Rfastp::catfastq(paste0(suppa_output, "_all_events.ioe"), dir(dirname(suppa_output), pattern = "*.ioe$", full.names = TRUE))
      paste0(suppa_output, "_all_events.ioe")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}
dr11_suppa_transcripts <- {
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      tmpdir <- tempdir()
      temp_gtf <- paste0(tempfile(), ".gtf")
      R.utils::gunzip(filename = dr11_BzippedGTF, destname = temp_gtf, remove = FALSE)
      suppa_output <- file.path(output_dir, "dr11_suppa_events", "dr11_suppa_events")
      dir.create(file.path(output_dir, "dr11_suppa_events"))
      args <- c("generateEvents", "-i", temp_gtf, "-e", "SE", "RI", "MX", "FL", "SS", "-f", "ioi", "-o", suppa_output)
      command <- "suppa.py"
      processx::run(command, args = args, echo = TRUE)
      unlink(temp_gtf)
      paste0(suppa_output, ".ioi")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}

FastQ Quality Control

This section descibes how quality control is performed on FastQ files prior to alignment.

FastQ quality is assessed here using the rfastp packages rfastp function.

To do this we will use the Rfastp package’s catFastQ function.

maxNfilter <- {
  5
}
minReadLength <- {
  15
}
qualityFilterPercent <- {
  40
}
qualityFilterPhred <- {
  15
}
Cut_062923_QC <- {
  Rfastp::rfastp(read1 = path.expand(Cut_062923_Pair1FQ), outputFastq = path.expand(file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_QC")), qualityFilterPhred = qualityFilterPhred, maxNfilter = maxNfilter, minReadLength = minReadLength, qualityFilterPercent = qualityFilterPercent)
  file.path(output_dir, paste0("Cut_062923_QC", ".json"))
}
Uncut_071223_QC <- {
  Rfastp::rfastp(read1 = path.expand(Uncut_071223_Pair1FQ), outputFastq = path.expand(file.path(output_dir, "Uncut_071223_QC")), qualityFilterPhred = qualityFilterPhred, maxNfilter = maxNfilter, minReadLength = minReadLength, qualityFilterPercent = qualityFilterPercent)
  file.path(output_dir, paste0("Uncut_071223_QC", ".json"))
}

Alignment of FastQ to reference genome (Rsubread)

This section descibes how fastQ is aligned to the reference genome using Rsubread.

Cut_062923_rsubread <- {
  tmpdir <- tempdir()
  tmpGTF <- paste0(tempfile(), ".gtf")
  R.utils::gunzip(filename = dr11_BzippedGTF, destname = tmpGTF, remove = FALSE)
  res <- Rsubread::subjunc(dr11_subreadindex, readfile1 = Cut_062923_Pair1FQ, output_file = file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_rsubread.bam"), nthreads = 1, useAnnotation = TRUE, annot.ext = tmpGTF, isGTF = TRUE, reportAllJunctions = TRUE, sortReadsByCoordinates = FALSE)
  file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_rsubread.bam")
}

Count reads in genes

To assign RNAseq reads to genes we can use the featureCounts function within the Rsubread package.

We have to provide our GTF file as our gene models to count over.

Cut_062923_Count <- {
  tmpdir <- tempdir()
  tmpGTF <- paste0(tempfile(), ".gtf")
  R.utils::gunzip(filename = dr11_BzippedGTF, destname = tmpGTF, remove = FALSE)
  Rsubread::featureCounts(files = Cut_062923_rsubread, isGTFAnnotationFile = TRUE, annot.ext = tmpGTF, useMetaFeatures = TRUE, strandSpecific = 0, isPairedEnd = FALSE, tmpDir = tempdir())
}

Cut_062923_fcCounts <- {
  Cut_062923_Count %>%
    extract2("counts") %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "GeneName") %>%
    write.csv(file = file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_fcCounts.txt"), sep = "\t", row.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE)
  file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_fcCounts.txt")
}
Cut_062923_fcStats <- {
  Cut_062923_Count %>%
    extract2("stat") %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    write.csv(file = file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_fcStats.txt"), sep = ",", row.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE)
  file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_fcStats.txt")
}

Sort and Index BAM files

Once we have have generated our aligned data as a BAM file from FastQ we can coordinate sort and index our BAM file to allow for use in other programs requiring these formats.

Cut_062923_sorted <- {
  Rsamtools::sortBam(Cut_062923_rsubread, file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_sorted"))
}

Create signal graph files (bigWigs)

Signal graphs files suchs as bigWigs can be used to review signal in genome browsers such as IGV.

Here we use the sorted aligned BAM file to create a bigWig of signal normalised to total aligned reads.

Cut_062923_bigwig <- {
  forCoverage <- Rsamtools::BamFile(file = Cut_062923_sorted, index = Cut_062923_index, yieldSize = 40 * 10^6, asMates = FALSE)
  total <- Rsamtools::idxstatsBam(file = Cut_062923_sorted, index = Cut_062923_index) %>%
    summarise(total = sum(mapped)) %>%
    pull(total)
  rle <- GenomicAlignments::coverage(forCoverage, weight = (1 / total) *
    10^6)
  rtracklayer::export.bw(rle, con = file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_sorted.bigwig"))
  file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_sorted.bigwig")
}
Uncut_071223_bigwig <- {
  forCoverage <- Rsamtools::BamFile(file = Uncut_071223_sorted, index = Uncut_071223_index, yieldSize = 40 * 10^6, asMates = FALSE)
  total <- Rsamtools::idxstatsBam(file = Uncut_071223_sorted, index = Uncut_071223_index) %>%
    summarise(total = sum(mapped)) %>%
    pull(total)
  rle <- GenomicAlignments::coverage(forCoverage, weight = (1 / total) *
    10^6)
  rtracklayer::export.bw(rle, con = file.path(output_dir, "Uncut_071223_sorted.bigwig"))
  file.path(output_dir, "Uncut_071223_sorted.bigwig")
}

Salmon quantification of transcript adundance

Salmon can quantify the transcript abundance for genes directly from the FastQs.

Here we calculate the number of reads per transcript using the salmon quant function.

Cut_062923_salmon <- {
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      command <- "salmon"
      args <- c(paste0("quant"), "-i", dr11_salmonIndex, "-l", "A", "-r", Cut_062923_Pair1FQ, "--validateMappings", "-o", file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_salmon"))
      processx::run(command, args = args, echo = TRUE)
      file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_salmon")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}

      processx::run(command, args = args, echo = TRUE)

Assess RNAseq quality metrics

Here we use the collectrnametrics function from the Picard software set to provide RNAseq specific QC metrics.

Cut_062923_rnametrics <- {
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      command <- "picard"
      args <- c("CollectRnaSeqMetrics", "-Xmx6g", paste0("REF_FLAT=", dr11_genepred), paste0("RIBOSOMAL_INTERVALS=", dr11_ribowhiteinterval), paste0("INPUT=", Cut_062923_sorted), paste0("OUTPUT=", file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_rnametrics.txt")), paste0("STRAND=", "NONE"), "VALIDATION_STRINGENCY=LENIENT")
      processx::run(command, args = args, echo = TRUE)
      file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_rnametrics.txt")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}

Assess alignment quality metrics

Picard from the BROAD institute provides a set of software to quality control high through-put sequencing data.

Here we use the collectalignmentmetrics function from the Picard software set to provide alignment QC metrics.

Cut_062923_alnmetrics <- {
  tempFasta <- paste0(tempfile(), ".fa.gz")
  file.copy(dr11_BzippedWhite, tempFasta)
  Herper::with_CondaEnv(general_env,
    {
      command <- "picard"
      args <- c("CollectAlignmentSummaryMetrics", "-Xmx6g", paste0("REFERENCE_SEQUENCE=", tempFasta), paste0("INPUT=", path.expand(Cut_062923_sorted)), paste0("OUTPUT=", file.path(path.expand(output_dir), "Cut_062923_alnmetrics.txt")), "VALIDATION_STRINGENCY=LENIENT")
      processx::run(command, args = args, echo = TRUE)
      file.path(output_dir, "Cut_062923_alnmetrics.txt")
    },
    pathToMiniConda = general_conda
  )
}
